author: Amos_Winter;
title: The cheap all-terrain wheelchair

aws-transcripts.transcript: living with a physical disability isn't easy anywhere in the world. But if you live in a country like the United States, there's certain appurtenances available to you that do make life easier. So if you're in a building, you can take an elevator. If you're crossing the street, you have sidewalk cutouts. And if you have to travel some distance farther than you can do under your own power, they're successful vehicles. And if you can't afford one of those, there's accessible public transportation. But in the developing world thinks they're quite different. There's 40,000,000 people who need a wheelchair but don't have one. And the majority of these people live in rural areas, where the only connections to community to employment to education are by traveling long distances on rough terrain, often under their own power, and the device is usually available to these people, are not made for that context, break down quickly and are hard to repair now. I started looking at wheelchairs in developing countries in 2005 when I spent the summer assessing the state of technology in Tanzania and I talked to wheelchair users with your manufacturers, disability groups and what stood out to me is that there wasn't a device available that was designed for rural areas that could go fast and efficiently on many types of terrain. So being a mechanical engineer being at M. I T. And having lost a resource is available to me, I thought I'd try to do something about it. Now, when you're talking about trying to travel long distances on rough terrain, I immediately thought of a mountain bike in a mountain. Bikes good at doing this because it has a gear train and you can shift to a lower gear if you have to climb a hill or go through mud or sand and you get a lot of torque but a low speed. And if you wanna go faster, say on pavement, you can shift to a high gear. You get less torque but higher speeds. So you know the logical evolution here is to just make a wheelchair with mountain bike components, which many people have done. But these are two products available in the US that would be difficult to transfer into developing countries because they're much, much too expensive.
